Introduction

When you want to fit a model to your data, often you need it in certain forms. That form is usually called normal. In Statistics, you will often see the normality assumption, or homoskedasticity, or independence etc. In this lab, we will cover the first one, transforming our data to satisfy normality, which will also solve the homoskedasticity.

Another topic that youâ€™ll cover this week is sampling. It is the magic behind statistics, the source of knowledge and undeniable truth behind all, well at least some. Accordingly, if you sample data randomly and calculate itâ€™s average, the number you can get is yet another random variable, and it is always normal. It will be detailed below.

In this tutorial you will learn how to:

  • Transforming the data using a parametric transformation method
  • Checking whether central limit theorem holds for the house dataset with non-normal even non-continuous random variables.

Getting Started

  1. Load house_subset.csv data.
  2. some packages including
  • tidyverse
  • qqtest
library('tidyverse')
theme_set(theme_minimal())
houses <- read.csv('../Lab 3/house_subset.csv') # choose your directory!

Letâ€™s see our pain. The below weird looking graph is unwelcomed in statistics. The reason is we want to explain a relationship between data points but the data is not spreaded evenly so that we can see it clearly:

library('ggExtra')
p <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=sqft_living, y=price)) + 
  geom_point(alpha=.1) + 
  geom_smooth(colour='firebrick')

ggMarginal(p, type = 'histogram')

Both variables are right skewed. When we draw the scatterplot, the data is grouped into certain intervals, and the rest is sprinkled all around. In other words, for low price and sqft_living values, the data is condensed around the line (variance is low) but for the higher values the data covers a wider range around the line (variance is high). This is known as heteroskedasticity and as you will see later when covering regressions, it is trouble.

We will show you how to obtain a normal looking dataset using transformations:

library(gridExtra)
g1 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=price)) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g2 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=sqrt(price))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g3 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=log(price))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

g4 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=sqft_living)) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g5 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=sqrt(sqft_living))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g6 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=log(sqft_living))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

grid.arrange(g1,g4,g2,g5,g3,g6)

price and sqft_living are originally right skewed. The sqrt transformation doesnâ€™t make it symmetric but the log-transformed one is pretty much symmetric.

library('qqtest')
qqtest(log(houses$price))

qqtest(log(houses$sqft_living))

The log transformation for sqft_living worked fine. qqtest shows it is in the envelope, so we cannot reject it is normal. But for price data we need more work. The edges are still out of the band.

Parametric Transformations

A transformation function can generalize the transformations by sqrt and log functions:

\[T(x,\alpha) = \frac{x^\alpha-1}{\alpha}\]

The above formula is a general form of the transformations you can use. For example, when \(\alpha = 1\), the above will be equal to the original series. When \(\alpha = 0.5\), it will be \(2\sqrt{x}-2\), which is equivalent to \(\sqrt{x}\). When \(x\rightarrow 0\), the equation goes to \(\ln x\).

It can be defined in R as:

tform <- function(x, alpha){
  if(alpha == 0) {log(x)} else {(x^alpha-1)/alpha}
}
g1 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(price,1))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g2 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(price,0.5))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g3 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(price,0))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

g4 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(sqft_living,1))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g5 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(sqft_living,.5))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g6 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(sqft_living,0))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

grid.arrange(g1,g4,g2,g5,g3,g6)

The advantage of the above is to allow for further values. For example for data needs transformation between log and sqrt, we can use values between 0 to 0.5. Or for left-skewed data we can use negative values:

g1 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(price,0))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g2 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(price,-0.25))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')
g3 <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=tform(price,-.5))) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

grid.arrange(g1,g2,g3)

We reached the sweet spot when alpha = -0.25.

Letâ€™s verify if it is normal enough:

qqtest(tform(houses$price,-0.25))

The line is not perfectly linear, but it is in the band. So it is hard to reject it is not normal.

After the transformation, the relation is easier to model:

p <- ggplot(houses, aes(x=log(sqft_living), y=tform(price,-.25))) + 
  geom_point(alpha=.1) + 
  geom_smooth(colour='firebrick')

ggMarginal(p, type = 'histogram')

The plot is now better, we can see the relation smoother than the previous case. The spreaded points are now gathered around the line

Sampling

In statistics, the central limit theorem suggests for any random variable \(X\):

\[Z \sim \frac{\bar X_i - \mu}{\sigma/\sqrt n}\]

In other words, for any data (assume that it is the population, \(P\)) whose average is \(\mu\) and standard deviation is \(\sigma\), if I take random samples from it (\(X_i \subset P\) for \(i \in 1,2,\dots,n\)) and calculate their averages (\(\bar X_i\)), then the distribution of \(\bar X_i\) must be standard normal. This must hold for any type of data.

The above also implies the following:

\[\bar X_i \sim N(\mu,\sigma^2/n)\]

Letâ€™s do it with sqft_living, price and bedrooms. All non-normal and one of them is discrete.

ggplot(houses, aes(x=sqft_living)) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

ggplot(houses, aes(x=price)) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

ggplot(houses, aes(x=bedrooms)) + 
  geom_histogram(colour='white')

Now letâ€™s take random samples and calculate their averages following the below procedure:

  • First, we will randomly select 200 rows from the data and repeat it 300 times,
  • and choose the data in these rows for each 300 groups,
  • then we will average the numbers fall in these rows, which will yield 300 averages, i.e.Â \(X_i\) for \(i \in [1,300]\):
# 1. sample(1:nrow(houses), 100)
# 2. houses$price[sample(1:nrow(houses), 100)]
# 3. mean(houses$price[sample(1:nrow(houses), 100)])

set.seed(156)
